profiles.title: Brachytherapy Treatment Phase
profiles.description: A summary of a phase of brachytherapy treatment that has been delivered. The scope is a treatment consisting of one or multiple identical fractions. A phase ends when there is a change in the irradiated volume, treatment fraction size, modality, or treatment technique.

profiles.title: Cancer Disease Status
profiles.description: A clinician's qualitative judgment on the current trend of the cancer, e.g., whether it is stable, worsening (progressing), or improving (responding). The judgment may be based a single type or multiple kinds of evidence, such as imaging data, assessment of symptoms, tumor markers, laboratory data, etc.

profiles.title: Cancer Genetic Variant
profiles.description: Records an alteration in the most common DNA nucleotide sequence. The term variant can be used to describe an alteration that may be benign, pathogenic, or of unknown significance. The term variant is increasingly being used in place of the term mutation.

profiles.title: Cancer Genomics Report
profiles.description: Genetic analysis summary report. The report may include one or more tests, with two distinct test types. The first type is a targeted mutation test, where a specific mutation on a specific gene is tested for. The result is either positive or negative for that mutation. The second type is a more general test for variants. This type of test returns the identity of variants found in a certain region of the genome.

profiles.title: Cancer Patient
profiles.description: A patient who has been diagnosed with or is receiving medical treatment for a malignant growth or tumor. The is the most essential profile in mCODE, since it is referenced by many other profiles. The only difference between the mCODE Patient profile and the [US Core Patient Profile](http://hl7.org/fhir/us/core/StructureDefinition-us-core-patient.html) is that Patient.deceased is a [must-support](https://www.hl7.org/fhir/profiling.html#mustsupport) element in mCODE.

profiles.title: Cancer Stage Group
profiles.description: The extent of the cancer in the body, according to a given cancer staging classification system, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy or based on pathologic analysis of a specimen.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Medication Administration
profiles.description: An episode of medication administration for a patient whose condition is related to a primary or secondary cancer condition. In the context of chemotherapy drugs, the medication administration in most cases is performed and documented by the provider.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Medication Request
profiles.description: A record of a medication prescription or consumption associated with cancer treatment. The medication may reported by the prescriber, prescribing organization, or patient. It does not have to be directly observed.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Surgical Procedure
profiles.description: A surgical action addressing a cancer condition. The scope of this profile has been narrowed to cancer-related procedures by constraining the reasonReference and reasonCode to cancer conditions, one of which is required.

profiles.title: Comorbidities Elixhauser
profiles.description: Comorbid condition checklist and optional risk score, using Elixhauser comorbidity categories as defined by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (H-CUP).

profiles.title: Comorbidities Parent
profiles.description: General structure for capturing comorbid conditions with respect to a primary ('index') condition. The specific set of comorbidities of interest in a given context are defined by slicing the components array. The same general approach can be applied to any comorbidity category checklist.

profiles.title: ECOG Performance Status
profiles.description: The Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) Performance Status represents the patient's functional status and is used to determine their ability to tolerate therapies in serious illness, specifically for chemotherapy. (Definition from: [LOINC](https://loinc.org/89262-0/))

profiles.title: Genetic Specimen
profiles.description: A small sample of blood, hair, skin, amniotic fluid (the fluid that surrounds a fetus during pregnancy), or other tissue which is excised from a subject for the purposes of genomics testing or analysis.

profiles.title: Genomic Region Studied
profiles.description: The area of the genome region referenced in testing for variants.

profiles.title: Karnofsky Performance Status
profiles.description: The Karnofsky Performance Status (KPS) is a tool used to measure a patient's functional status. It can be used to compare the effectiveness of different therapies and to help assess the prognosis of certain patients, such as those with certain cancers. The KPS score ranges from 0 to 100 in intervals of 10. Higher scores are associated with better functional status, with 100 representing no symptoms or evidence of disease, and 0 representing death.

profiles.title: Primary Cancer Condition
profiles.description: Records the the primary cancer condition, the original or first tumor in the body (Definition from: [NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms](https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/primary-tumor)). Cancers that are not clearly secondary (i.e., of uncertain origin or behavior) should be documented as primary.

profiles.title: Radiotherapy Course Summary
profiles.description: A summary of a course of radiotherapy delivered to a patient. It records the treatment intent, termination reason, modalities, techniques, number of sessions, and doses delivered to one or more body volumes. To describe the treatment in more detail, use either TeleradiotherapyTreatmentPhase or BrachytherapyTreatmentPhase, which should reference this summary through their partOf elements. Whether the course has been fully delivered or stopped is indicated in the status element.

profiles.title: Radiotherapy Volume
profiles.description: A volume of the body used in radiotherapy planning or treatment delivery.

profiles.title: Secondary Cancer Condition
profiles.description: Records the history of secondary neoplasms, including location(s) and the date of onset of metastases. A secondary cancer results from the spread (metastasization) of cancer from its original site (Definition from: NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms).

profiles.title: TNM Distant Metastases Category
profiles.description: Category describing the extent of a tumor metastasis in remote anatomical locations, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: TNM Primary Tumor Category
profiles.description: Category of the primary tumor, based on its size and extent, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: TNM Regional Nodes Category
profiles.description: Category of the presence or absence of metastases in regional lymph nodes, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: Teleradiotherapy Treatment Phase
profiles.description: A summary of a phase of teleradiotherapy treatment that has been delivered. The scope is a treatment consisting of one or multiple identical fractions. A phase ends whenever there is a change in the irradiated volume, dose per fraction, modality, or technique.

profiles.title: Tumor
profiles.description: Identifies a tumor that has not been removed from the body. Whenever possible, a single resource conforming to this profile will be used to track a tumor over time (as opposed to creating new Tumor-conforming BodyStructure resources each time that tumor is measured). Use [TumorSpecimen](StructureDefinition-mcode-tumor-specimen.html) to represent the tumor after removal from the body.

profiles.title: Tumor Marker Test
profiles.description: The result of a tumor marker test. Tumor marker tests are generally used to guide cancer treatment decisions and monitor treatment, as well as to predict the chance of recovery and cancer recurrence.

profiles.title: Tumor Size
profiles.description: Records the dimensions of a tumor

profiles.title: Tumor Specimen
profiles.description: Represents a tumor after it has been removed from the body. Prior to excision, use [Tumor](StructureDefinition-mcode-tumor.html) (a BodyStructure) instead. If this tumor was represented by [Tumor](StructureDefinition-mcode-tumor.html) while still in the body, use `identifier` to associate with that resource.

profiles.title: mCODE Patient Bundle
profiles.description: A collection of data for an mCODE cancer patient.

profiles.title: mCODE Patient Group
profiles.description: A group of patients included in the scope of mCODE, whose cancer-related resources conform to mCODE profiles.

Concepts classifying the person into a named category of humans sharing common history, traits, geographical origin or nationality.  The race codes used to represent these concepts are based upon the [CDC Race and Ethnicity Code Set Version 1.0](http://www.cdc.gov/phin/resources/vocabulary/index.html) which includes over 900 concepts for representing race and ethnicity of which 921 reference race.  The race concepts are grouped by and pre-mapped to the 5 OMB race categories:

   - American Indian or Alaska Native
   - Asian
   - Black or African American
   - Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander
   - White.

The 5 race category codes according to the [OMB Standards for Maintaining, Collecting, and Presenting Federal Data on Race and Ethnicity, Statistical Policy Directive No. 15, as revised, October 30, 1997](https://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/fedreg_1997standards).
Plain text representation of the race concept(s).

Concepts classifying the person into a named category of humans sharing common history, traits, geographical origin or nationality.  The ethnicity codes used to represent these concepts are based upon the [CDC ethnicity and Ethnicity Code Set Version 1.0](http://www.cdc.gov/phin/resources/vocabulary/index.html) which includes over 900 concepts for representing race and ethnicity of which 43 reference ethnicity.  The ethnicity concepts are grouped by and pre-mapped to the 2 OMB ethnicity categories: - Hispanic or Latino - Not Hispanic or Latino.

The 2 ethnicity category codes according to the [OMB Standards for Maintaining, Collecting, and Presenting Federal Data on Race and Ethnicity, Statistical Policy Directive No. 15, as revised, October 30, 1997](https://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/fedreg_1997standards).
Plain text representation of the ethnicity concept(s).

The patient, or group of patients, location, or device this observation is about and into whose record the observation is placed. If the actual focus of the observation is different from the subject (or a sample of, part, or region of the subject), the `focus` element or the `code` itself specifies the actual focus of the observation.

The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.

valueSets.title: Brachytherapy Modality Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the modalities of brachytherapy procedures.

valueSets.title: Brachytherapy Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the techniques of brachytherapy (internal or surface radiation) procedures.

valueSets.title: Cancer Body Location Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the location(s) of primary or secondary cancer. The value set includes all codes from the SNOMED CT body structure hierarchy (codes descending from 123037004 'Body Structure'). The cancer body location may also be expressed using ICD-O-3 topography codes, however, those codes are not included here due to intellectual property restrictions. These topography terms have four-character codes that run from C00.0 to C80.9 [ref](https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/96612/9789241548496_eng.pdf). Only SNOMED CT and ICD-O-3 are considered conformant.

valueSets.title: Cancer Disease Status Evidence Type Value Set
valueSets.description: The type of evidence backing up the clinical determination of cancer progression.

valueSets.title: Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: A broad cancer-related value set containing both primary and secondary tumor types, with codes from ICD-10 and SNOMED CT, including both diagnosis and histology/morphology/behavior codes. ICD-O-3 morphology codes may also be used and are considered conformant to the specification. For SNOMED, the value set includes all codes descending from 363346000 'Malignant neoplastic disease (disorder)' and 108369006 'Neoplasm (morphologic abnormality)'.

valueSets.title: Cancer-Related Surgical Procedure Value Set
valueSets.description: Includes surgical procedure codes from SNOMED CT, ICD-10-PCS and CPT. The value set may be a superset of cancer surgery codes, but narrowing the set further risks eliminating potentially useful and relevant codes.

valueSets.title: Stage Group Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for Stage Group, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: Cancer Staging System Value Set
valueSets.description: System used for staging.

valueSets.title: ClinVar Value Set
valueSets.description: Value set of human genetic variants, drawn from [ClinVar](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/clinvar/). The codes in this value set refer to the ClinVar Variation ID, or the identifier for the variant or set of variants that were interpreted. [Source: NCBI ClinVar Data Dictionary](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/projects/clinvar/ClinVarDataDictionary.pdf)

valueSets.title: Condition Status Trend Value Set
valueSets.description: How patient's given disease, condition, or ability is trending.

valueSets.title: DNA Change Type Value Set
valueSets.description: DNA Change Type of a variant

valueSets.title: Genetic Specimen Type Value Set
valueSets.description: The type of specimen analyzed in a genetic test. The values are taken from code system http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/v2-0487, and represent a subset of HL7 Version 2 Table 0487 (http://hl7.org/fhir/v2/0487).

valueSets.title: HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee Gene Names Value Set
valueSets.description: HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee Gene Names Value Set

valueSets.title: Human Genome Variation Society Sequence Variant Nomenclature Value Set
valueSets.description: HGVS nomenclature is used to report and exchange information regarding variants found in DNA, RNA, and protein sequences.

valueSets.title: Histology Morphology Behavior Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes representing the structure, arrangement, and behavioral characteristics of malignant neoplasms, and cancer cells. Inclusion criteria: in situ neoplasms and malignant neoplasms. Exclusion criteria: benign neoplasms and neoplasms of unspecified behavior. Note: ICD-O-3 morphology codes are referenced in the logical definition but not expanded in the value set for intellectual property reasons. For primary cancers, the ICD-O-3 behavior suffix should be /1, /2, or /3. For secondary cancers, the ICD-O-3 behavior suffix should be /6.

valueSets.title: Location Qualifier Value Set
valueSets.description: Qualifiers to refine a body structure or location. These include qualifiers for laterality, relative location, directionality, number, and plane.

valueSets.title: Observation Codes for Distant Metastases Category
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for distant metastases (M) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Observation Codes for Primary Tumor Category
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for primary tumor (T) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Observation Codes for Regional Node Category
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for regional node (N) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Observation Codes for Stage Group Category
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for stage group observations.

valueSets.title: Present-Absent-Unknown
valueSets.description: Value set used in association with phenomena that can be observed as being present or absent, such as a finding, organism, or physical object.

valueSets.title: Primary or Uncertain Behavior Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description:
Types of primary malignant neoplastic disease, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM. 

For SNOMED CT coding, use a code from the disorder hierarchy under SNOMED CT 363346000 'Malignant neoplastic disease (disorder)' excluding codes descending from SNOMED CT 128462008 'Secondary malignant neoplastic disease (disorder)'. If body location is not precoordinated (i.e., implied by the code), the site of the primary tumor should be specified in the body site attribute. 

For ICD-10-CM coding, use one of the codes given in this value set representing primary malignant neoplasms and neoplasms of uncertain or unspecified behavior.

Note that ICD-O-3 specifies morphology and topography, not disorder. If ICD-O-3 is used, the primary cancer disorder code must be specifically be SNOMED CT 363346000 'Malignant neoplastic disease (disorder)'. The ICD-O-3 morphology and topography codes should be entered in the HistologyMorphologyBehavior and body location fields, respectively.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Modality Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the modalities of external beam and brachytherapy radiation procedures, for use with radiotherapy summaries.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the techniques of external beam and brachytherapy radiation procedures, for use with radiotherapy summaries.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Treatment Location Qualifier Value Set
valueSets.description: Various modifiers that can be applied to body locations where radiotherapy treatments can be directed.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Treatment Location Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the body locations where radiotherapy treatments can be directed.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Volume Type Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the types of body volumes used in radiotherapy planning and treatment. The value set includes the most common codes from DICOM CID 9534 Radiotherapy Targets (UID 1.2.840.10008.6.1.1244) and adds a code for Organs at Risk (OAR).

valueSets.title: Secondary Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description:
Types of secondary malignant neoplastic disease, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM. 

* SNOMED CT coding: Use a code from the disorder hierarchy under secondary malignant neoplastic disease (SNOMED CT 128462008).
* ICD-10-CM coding: Use one of the codes given in this value set representing secondary malignant neoplasms and neoplasms of uncertain or unspecified behavior. If body site is not precoordinated (implied by the code), it should be specified separately using the body location.

Note that ICD-O-3 specifies morphology and topography, not disorder; in this case that the disorder code must be SNOMED CT 128462008 (Secondary malignant neoplastic disease).The ICD-O-3 morphology and topography codes should be entered in the HistologyMorphologyBehavior and bodySite fields, respectively.

valueSets.title: Teleradiotherapy Modality Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the modalities of teleradiotherapy (external beam) procedures.

valueSets.title: Teleradiotherapy Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the techniques of teleradiotherapy (external beam) procedures.

valueSets.title: TNM Distant Metastases Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the M category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: TNM Primary Tumor Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the T category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: TNM Regional Nodes Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the N category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: Treatment Intent Value Set
valueSets.description: The purpose of a treatment.

valueSets.title: Treatment Termination Reason Value Set
valueSets.description: Values used to describe the reasons for stopping a treatment or episode of care. Includes code for 'treatment completed' as well as codes for unplanned (early) stoppage. Applies to medications and other treatments that take place over a period of time, such as radiation treatments.

valueSets.title: Tumor Marker Test Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes representing tests for tumor markers. This value set of LOINC codes is not comprehensive and can be extended. Other vocabularies can be used only if the test of interest is not covered by LOINC. Tumor marker tests differ from genetic tests in that they measure levels of protein or other substances produced downstream from RNA protein synthesis.

valueSets.title: Methods for measuring tumor size
valueSets.description: Code for methods of measuring tumor size, including physical examination, pathology, and imaging.

valueSets.title: Units of tumor size value set
valueSets.description: Acceptable units for measuring tumor size

extensions.title: Specific Condition Code for Comorbidity
extensions.description: An extension for representing a specific condition code corresponding to the comorbid condition category.

extensions.title: Specific Condition Reference for Comorbidity
extensions.description: An extension for representing a reference to a condition resource corresponding to the comorbid condition category.

extensions.title: Condition related to resource
extensions.description: The resource has an unspecified relationship with a Condition.

extensions.title: Evidence Type
extensions.description: Categorization of the kind of evidence used as input to the clinical judgment. This corresponds to both the S and O in SOAP.

extensions.title: Histology-Morphology-Behavior
extensions.description: An extension describing the morphologic and behavioral characteristics of the cancer.

extensions.title: Location Qualifier
extensions.description: Qualifier to refine an body location. These include qualifiers for laterality, relative location, directionality, number, and plane.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Dose Delivered To Body Volume
extensions.description: Dose parameters for one radiotherapy volume.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Fractions Delivered
extensions.description: The total number of fractions (treatment divisions) actually delivered for this volume.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Modality
extensions.description: Extension capturing a modality of external beam or brachytherapy radiation procedures.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Number of Sessions
extensions.description: The number of sessions in a course of radiotherapy.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Technique
extensions.description: Extension capturing a technique of external beam or brachytherapy radiation procedures.

extensions.title: Termination Reason
extensions.description: A code explaining an unplanned or premature termination of a plan of treatment, course of medication, or research study.

codeSystems.title: Elixhauser Comorbidity Categories
codeSystems.description: A set of codes representing the comorbidity categories originally defined by Elixhauser, and updated by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (H-CUP).

codeSystems.title: mCODE Catch Codes
codeSystems.description: Codes needed for positive identification of certain types of instances, more specifically, to uniquely associate instances with slices when they are used in bundles. The codes in this code system are used when a concept falls outside of the defined set of codes. They make it possible to use 'required' bindings where 'extensible' bindings would result an instance matching multiple slices and thus trigger validation errors.

codeSystems.title: mCODE Resource Identifier Code System
codeSystems.description:
Concepts describing instance types, to be used in the `code` element of instances. These codes were created because no appropriate concept could be found in established vocabularies. These concepts are analogous to LOINC codes for laboratory observations: they identify the type of thing an instance represents.

Please note that while these codes may imply conformance to the profiles that use them, they are not synonymous with profiles and do not serve the same purpose in a FHIR resource for several reasons:

1. An instance of a resource like Group, Observation, or Procedure may conform to multiple profiles, but may only have one 'type of thing' as determined by the value of `code` (which has a maximum cardinality of 1).
2. `Procedure.code`, `Observation.code`, and `Group.code` elements require a [CodeableConcept data type](http://www.hl7.org/fhir/datatypes.html#CodeableConcept), which can be satisfied with a code from this code system. In contrast, a profile is identified with a [canonical URL](http://www.hl7.org/fhir/structuredefinition-definitions.html#StructureDefinition.url), which is represented by a [URI data type](http://www.hl7.org/fhir/datatypes.html#uri). In other words, a profile's canonical URL belongs in the `meta.profile` element, whereas the codes in this code system belong in `Resource.code` elements.
3. The same `code` can correspond to more than one profile (although not the case here).
